<DOC><DOCNO> AP900330-0126 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-30-90 2236EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-AuditoriumPhantom     03-30 0242</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Auditorium Phantom,0248</SECOND><HEAD>High School Student Caught Living in Secret Auditorium Apartment</HEAD><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A teen-age Phantom of the Opera lived for sixmonths above the stage of his high school auditorium in a secretapartment equipped with a television, videocassette recorder andmicrowave oven, police said.   Police discovered Robert Davis' living arrangements on Mondaywhen they saw someone using a key sneak into the auditorium at JohnH. Francis Polytechnic High School in suburban Sun Valley.   ``Maybe he was like `The Phantom of the Opera' _ hiding here,hiding there,'' Detective Oscar Carballo said, adding he'd livedthere about six months. ``I just don't understand how he could beliving there without anyone knowing it.''   Officers found Davis, 18, a student at the school, and threevisiting students inside the living area equipped with a bed,refrigerator, telephone and heater, police said.   Davis fled but was arrested the next day. The other three youthswere captured inside the school, officials said.   All were booked for investigation of burglary, Carballo said.Many items furnishing the apartment apparently had been taken fromthe school, police said.   Principal Virginia A. Holt said staff members knew someone witha key was entering rooms and taking things, such as the microwaveoven, but they did not know about the apartment. She refused torelease further information about the boy.   Sun Valley is a San Fernando Valley community about 20 milesnorthwest of downtown.</TEXT></DOC>